<subSubSection box="[199,1015,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="494" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,1015,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name alludes to the red colour of the forewings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="494" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,620,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">Remarks</emphasis>
. Among the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[578,694,620,643]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[578,694,620,643]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">Signoretia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this species is probably the largest, most robust and colourful. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmidt" authorityName="Schmidt" box="[274,529,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumatrana">
<emphasis box="[274,426,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">S. sumatrana</emphasis>
Schmidt
</taxonomicName>
from which it differs in having orange reddish coloration. Both species have similar forewing venation in the apical region (
<figureCitation box="[677,762,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 46" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1915,1938]" captionTargetBox="[227,1359,204,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[216,1371,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 46. Habitus and wings of species of Signoretia. 31 – 36. S. sahyadrica sp. nov., 31 – 32 holotype male; 33 – 34. Paratype female. 35 – 36. Paratype male; 37 – 38. S. similaris sp. nov., holotype male; 39 – 40. S. sinuata sp. nov., holotype male; 41 – 42. S. sinuata, paratype female; 43 – 45. S. sumatrana Schmidt, holoype male; 46. S. tagalica Baker, syntype. Figs 31, 33, 35, 37, 39, 41, 43, 46. Dorsal aspect. Figs 32, 34, 36, 38, 40, 42, 45. Lateral aspect. 44. Fore and hind wings." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167194/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">Figs 44</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[816,859,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 151 – 161" captionStartId="26.[151,264,1905,1928]" captionTargetBox="[164,1414,209,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[150,1436,193,1884]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 151 – 161. Signoretia rubra sp. nov. 151. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 152. Head and thorax, profile; 153. Male genital capsule, lateral view; 154. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 155. Connective, dorsal view; 156. Aedeagus and ventral process, posterior view; 157. Style, lateral view; 158. Pygofer ventral process, lateral view; 159. Aedeagus and ventral process, anterodorsal view; 160. Aedeagus and ventral process lateral view; 161. Forewing venation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167205/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="494">161</figureCitation>
) and have a forked ventral pygofer process.
</paragraph>
